<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-income-tax-ii" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Income Tax II</title>
    <!--  -->
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurement and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.4 Commercial Arithmetic
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title> 
                    <p>
                        Compute income tax using taxation table
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        11
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>

        <ol>

            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>

            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To understand how PAYE is calculated using different tax bands and how tax relief affects the amount of tax paid.
                </p>
            </li>

            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Organize learners into groups and guide them to complete the <em>Income Level vs. Tax Effect</em> table. Encourage discussion on why people with different incomes pay different amounts of tax. Help learners identify how tax relief reduces the final tax payable.
                </p>
            </li>

        </ol>

    </axiom>
        <activity>
            <statement>

                <p>
                    <term>Work in Groups</term> of <m>3 - 4</m>
                </p>

                <p>
                    In real taxation systems, income is not taxed at a single rate. Instead, different portions of income are taxed at different rates. This system is called a <term>progressive tax system</term>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Use the Kenyan progressive Tax table <xref ref="table-monthly-tax-rates" /> below for the activity.
                </p>

                <p>
                    A school clerk earns a monthly taxable income of Ksh <m>24,000</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Calculate:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                His gross monthly tax, (Use the formula; <m>\text{Gross monthly tax} \; =\; \text{Tax Band} \; \times \; \text{Rate} </m>)?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                His Net monthly tax, (Use the formula; <m>\text{Net monthly tax} \; =\; \text{Gross monthly tax} \; - \; \text{Monthly Relief} </m>)?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                His Net monthly pay, (Use the formula; <m>\text{Net monthly pay} \; =\; \text{Taxable income} \; - \; \text{Net monthly tax} </m>)
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>

                <p>
                    <alert>Discuss in Groups:</alert>
                </p>

                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Why the government apply relief after tax is calculated and not before?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                What happens to take-home pay when relief increases?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Why do higher income earners contribute more tax?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>

                <p>
                    Suppose a worker earns a higher salary that falls into multiple tax bands. Discuss how tax is applied on different portions of income rather than the whole income at once.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </activity>

    

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>

        <p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <title>Suggested Time</title>
                    <p>
                        10 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <title>Objective</title>
                    <p>
                        To understand how PAYE is calculated using different tax bands and how tax reliefs affect the final tax payable.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>

        <paragraphs>
            <title>Discussion of Learner Findings</title>

            <ol>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Discussion:</alert> Review the activity and remind learners that different parts of an income may be taxed at different rates. Explain that a higher tax rate is not applied to the entire income but only to the amount that falls within that tax band.
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Discussion:</alert> Use an example to show how income is divided among the tax bands. Calculate the tax for each band separately and then find the total tax payable.
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Discussion:</alert> Show learners how personal relief and insurance relief reduce the total tax payable. Explain that net pay is obtained after deducting PAYE and any other deductions from the gross salary.
                    </p>
                </li>

            </ol>

        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>
    <insight>
        <p>
            Income tax is calculated using a progressive system where income is divided into different portions, and each portion is taxed at its own rate according to predefined tax brackets. This means that lower portions of income are taxed at lower rates, while only the income that falls within higher brackets is taxed at higher rates. The total tax payable is obtained by summing the tax from each bracket, after which any applicable reliefs are deducted to obtain the final amount of tax due.
        </p>
        <p>
                    The table below shows the Kenyan progressive tax rates for different income levels. We will be using it to calculate tax for workers in the next sections.
                </p>
                
        <table xml:id="table-monthly-tax-rates">
            <title>Kenyan Progressive Tax System</title>
            <tabular left="medium" right="medium" top="medium" bottom="medium">
                <row header="yes">
                    <cell>Tax Bands</cell>
                    <cell>Annual</cell>
                    <cell>Monthly</cell>
                    <cell>Rates</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>On the first </cell>
                    <cell><m>\text{Ksh}\;288,000</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>\text{Ksh}\;24,000</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>10 \%</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>On the next</cell>
                    <cell> <m> \text{Ksh}\;100,000</m></cell>
                    <cell> <m> \text{Ksh}\;8,333</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>25\%</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>On the next</cell>
                    <cell> <m> \text{Ksh}\;5,612,000</m></cell>
                    <cell> <m> \text{Ksh}\;467,667</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>30\%</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>On the next </cell>
                    <cell><m> \text{Ksh}\;3,600,000</m></cell>
                    <cell><m> \text{Ksh}\;300,000</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>30.25\%</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>On all income in excess of </cell>
                    <cell><m> \text{Ksh}\;9,600,000</m></cell>
                    <cell><m> \text{Ksh}\;32,333</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>35\%</m></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>

        <p>
            Personal Relief of Kshs. <m>28,800</m> per annum (Kshs. <m>2,400</m> per month) is allowed.
        </p>

        <p>
            The taxation process involves:
        </p>

        <p>
            <md>
                <mrow> \text{Gross Tax} = \amp \; \text{Taxable Income} \times \text{Rate(s)} </mrow>
                <mrow> \text{Net Tax (PAYE)} = \amp \; \text{Gross Tax} - \text{Reliefs} </mrow>
            </md>
        </p>
        <p>
            As a person's income increases, the additional income falls into higher tax bands and is taxed at higher rates. However, the higher rate applies only to the income within that band, not to the entire income.
        </p>
        <p>
            To determine the amount of tax payable:
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol marker="(i)">
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Calculate the taxable income.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Identify the amount of income that falls within each tax band.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Calculate the tax for each band separately.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Add the taxes from all bands to obtain the Gross Tax.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Subtract any eligible tax reliefs to obtain the Net Tax (PAYE).
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>

        <p>
            Understanding progressive taxation helps workers interpret their payslips and appreciate how taxes are calculated from their earnings.
        </p>
    </insight>

    <!-- Add further instruction (not in a block) to develop ideas as needed -->

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- Add at least 3 examples -->

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Mr.Masimba earns a basic salary of sh. <m>150,000</m> per month. In addition, he gets a medical allowance of sh. <m>20,000</m>, and a house allowance of sh. <m>30,000</m>. Use the tax bracket from <xref ref="table-monthly-tax-rates" /> to calculate his Net annual tax?
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> \text{Taxable income per month}\; =\amp \; \text{sh.}\;(150,000 + 20,000 + 30,000) </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp =\; \text{sh.}\; 200,000</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Tax due
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> \text{First slab}\; \amp = \;\text{sh.} 24,000 \;  \times \frac{10}{100} = \text{sh.}\; 2,400 </mrow>
                    <mrow>\text{Second slab}\; \amp = \;\text{sh.} \; 8,333 \times \frac{25}{100} = \text{sh.}\; 2083.25 </mrow>
                    <mrow>\text{Third slab}\; \amp = \;\text{sh.} \; 167,667 \times \frac{30}{100} = \text{sh.}\; 50,300.1 </mrow>
                    <mrow> \text{Gross tax} \; \amp =\; \text{sh.} \;54,783.35</mrow>
                    <mrow> \text{Less personal relief} \; \amp = \;\text{sh.}\; 2,400 </mrow>
                    <mrow> \text{Net monthly tax}\; \amp = \;\text{sh.}\; 52,383.35 </mrow>
                    <mrow> \text{Net annual tax}\; \amp = \;\text{sh.}\; 52,383.35 \times 12 </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \; \text{Ksh} \;628,600.2 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                The Net annual tax for Mr. Masimba is Ksh <m>52,383.35</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Mr. Mwangi is a resident employee in Nairobi earning a Gross Monthly Salary of KSh <m>120,000</m>. His employer deducts a NSSF contribution of KSh <m>2,160</m>. Use the tax bracket from <xref ref="table-monthly-tax-rates" /> to calculate Mr. Mwangi's Net income payable for the month.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Monthly Taxable Income
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Taxable Income} \; = \amp\; \text{Gross monthly salary}\; - \;\text{Deductions} </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp\; 120,000 - 2,160 </mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp \; \text{Ksh}\; 117,840 </mrow>
                </md>
                
            </p>
            <p>
                Gross monthly tax
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> \text{First slab}\; \amp = \;\text{sh.} 24,000 \;  \times \frac{10}{100} = \text{sh.}\; 2,400 </mrow>
                    <mrow>\text{Second slab}\; \amp = \;\text{sh.} \; 8,333 \times \frac{25}{100} = \text{sh.}\; 2083.25 </mrow>
                    <mrow>\text{Third slab}\; \amp = \;\text{sh.} \; 85,507 \times \frac{30}{100} = \text{sh.}\; 25,652.1 </mrow>
                    <mrow> \text{Gross tax} \; \amp =\; \text{sh.} \;30,135.35</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Net monthly tax
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Net monthly income}\; = \amp \; \text{Gross mothly income}\; - \; \text{Relief} </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp\; 30,135.35 - 2,400 </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \;\text{Ksh}\; 27,735.35 </mrow>
                </md>
                
            </p>
            <p>
                Net monthly income
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Net monthly income} \; = \amp \; \text{Taxable income} \; - \; \text{Net tax} </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \; 117,840 - 27,735.35 </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \; \text{Ksh}\; 90,104.65 </mrow>
                </md>
                
            </p>
            <p>
                The Net monthly income for Mr. Mwangi is <m>\text{Ksh}\; 90,104.65</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Mr. Ondiala is employed in the United States and earns an annual basic salary equivalent to <m>\text{Ksh}\; 15,000,000</m>. He is provided with housing by his employer, and the value of the housing benefit is assessed at <m>15\%</m> of his basic salary. In addition, he receives a housing allowance of <m>\text{Ksh}\; 100,000</m> per month and a transport allowance of <m>\text{Ksh}\; 30,000</m> per month. He contributes <m>\text{Ksh}\; 25,000</m> per month to a retirement scheme and pays <m>\text{Ksh}\; 5,000</m> per month for medical insurance.
            </p>
            <p>
                Use the progressive tax brackets <xref ref="table-monthly-tax-rates" /> to calculate his net monthly income.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Mr. Ondiala's annual taxable income;
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Gross annual salary} \amp\; = \;\text{Basic salary}\; + 15 \% \times \;\text{Basic salary}  </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp\; 15,000,000 + 15 \% \times 15,000,000 </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp\; \text{Ksh}\; 17,250,000 </mrow>
                </md>
                
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Total annual allowances} \; = \amp\; \text{House allowance}\; + \;\text{Transport allowance} </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \; 12 \times 100,000 + 12 \times 30,000 </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp\; \text{Ksh}\; 1,560,000 </mrow>
                </md>
                
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Total annual deductions} \; = \amp\; \text{Retirement scheme}\; + \;\text{Medical insurance} </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \; 12 \times 25,000 + 12 \times 5,000 </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp\; \text{Ksh}\; 360,000 </mrow>
                </md>
                
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Taxable income} \; \amp = \text{Gross salary}\; + \text{Total allowances}\; - \; \text{Total deductions}  </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp\; 17,250,000 + 1,560,000 - 360,000 </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \;\text{Ksh}\; 18,450,000 \;\text{per annum} </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                His Gross annual tax
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> \text{First slab}\; \amp = \;\text{Ksh.} 288,000 \;  \times \frac{10}{100} = \text{Ksh.}\; 28,800 </mrow>
                    <mrow>\text{Second slab}\; \amp = \;\text{Ksh.} \; 100,000 \times \frac{25}{100} = \text{Ksh.}\; 25,000 </mrow>
                    <mrow>\text{Third slab}\; \amp = \;\text{Ksh.} \; 5,612,000 \times \frac{30}{100} = \text{Ksh.}\; 1,683,600 </mrow>
                    <mrow>\text{Forth slab}\; \amp = \;\text{ksh.} \; 3,600,000 \times \frac{30.25}{100} = \text{Ksh.}\; 1,089,000 </mrow>
                    <mrow>\text{Fifth slab}\; \amp = \;\text{Ksh.} \; 8,850,000 \times \frac{35}{100} = \text{Ksh.}\; 3,097,500 </mrow>
                    <mrow> \text{Total Gross tax} \; \amp =\; \text{Ksh.} \;5,923,900</mrow>
                </md>
                
            </p>
            <p>
                His total Gross tax is <m>\text{Ksh.} \;5,923,900</m> annually.
            </p>
            <p>
                His Net tax;
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Net tax}\; = \amp \; \text{Gross tax} \; - \; \text{Relief} </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \; 5,923,900 - 28,800 </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp\; \text{Ksh.} \;5,895,100 </mrow>
                </md>
                
            </p>
            <p>
                His Net tax is <m>\text{Ksh.} \;5,895,100</m> annually.
            </p>
            <p>
                His Net monthly income;
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Net annual income}\; = \amp\; \text{Taxable income}\; - \; \text{Net tax} </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \; 18,450,000 - 5,895,100 </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \; \text{Ksh}\; 12,554,900 </mrow>
                </md>
                
            </p>
            <p>
                His Net monthly income is given by;
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Net monthly income}\; = \amp \; \frac{\text{Net annual income}}{12} </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp\; \frac{12,554,900}{12} </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp\; \text{Ksh}\; 1,046,241.667 \text{per month} </mrow>
                </md>
                
            </p>
            <p>
                The Net monthly income is <m>\text{Ksh}\; 1,046,241.667</m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    
    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/assessment-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- If STACK questions are included, uncomment this: -->

    <!-- <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/checkpoint.ptx" /> -->

    <!-- Add STACK exercises if made -->

    <!-- Add static exercises -->

    <exercises>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Jacob is employed by the county government, he earns a monthly basic salary of <m>\text{Ksh}\; 120,000</m>. He is housed by her employer, and the value of the housing benefit is assessed at <m>15\%</m> of her basic salary. He also receives a transport allowance of <m>\text{Ksh}\; 10,000</m> per month.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Every month, <m>\text{Ksh}\; 5,000</m> is deducted for pension contributions and <m>\text{Ksh}\; 2,000</m> for medical insurance. Calculate her monthly net income.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>\approx \text{Ksh}\; 106,317</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Mr. Kamau's net monthly income is <m>\text{Ksh}\; 75,350</m>. He contributes <m>\text{Ksh}\; 4,000</m> per month to a retirement scheme and pays <m>\text{Ksh}\; 1,000</m> per month for medical insurance. Determine Mr. Kamau's monthly taxable income.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>\text{Ksh}\; 96,762</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                After all deductions, taxes, and personal relief have been applied, Mr. Ben's net annual income is <m>\text{Ksh}\; 3,000,000</m>. He is provided with housing by his employer, and the value of the housing benefit is assessed at <m>15\%</m> of his basic salary. He contributes <m>\text{Ksh}\; 120,000</m> per year to a retirement scheme and pays <m>\text{Ksh}\; 24,000</m> per year for medical insurance.
            </p>
            <p>
                Determine Mr. Ben's annual basic salary.
            </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>\text{Ksh} \; 3,738,385.09</m>
                </p>
            </answer>      
        </exercise>  
    </exercises>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation Strategies</title>

        <table>
            <title>Differentiation Matrix for Progressive Income Tax</title>

            <tabular halign="left" top="medium" bottom="medium" left="medium" right="medium">

                <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                    <cell>Learner Group</cell>
                    <cell>Strategy &amp; Learning Experience</cell>
                </row>

                <row bottom="minor">
                    <cell><alert>Struggling Learners (Support)</alert></cell>
                    <cell>
                        <p>
                            Begin with simple tax calculations involving one tax band. Guide learners through each step and provide worked examples.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Use tables and worksheets to help learners identify the taxable amount in each band before calculating the tax due.
                        </p>
                    </cell>
                </row>

                <row bottom="minor">
                    <cell><alert>On-Level Learners (Core)</alert></cell>
                    <cell>
                        <p>
                            Learners calculate tax for incomes that fall within different tax bands. They determine gross pay, tax payable, and net income using given tax rates.
                        </p>
                    </cell>
                </row>

                <row>
                    <cell><alert>Advanced Learners (Challenge)</alert></cell>
                    <cell>
                        <p>
                            Give learners problems that require finding missing values such as gross income or taxable income from the net income.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Encourage learners to compare the amount of tax paid by people in different income groups and explain their findings.
                        </p>
                    </cell>
                </row>

            </tabular>

        </table>

        <paragraphs>
            <title>Teacher Guidance</title>

            <ol>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Classroom Organization:</alert> Provide additional support to learners who experience difficulty with tax calculations while allowing other groups to work independently.
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Peer Support:</alert> Encourage learners who complete their work early to assist others by explaining the calculation steps.
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Extension Activity:</alert> Ask learners to investigate how a change in income affects the amount of tax paid and the net income received.
                    </p>
                </li>

            </ol>

        </paragraphs>

    </axiom>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/assessment-methods.ptx" />

